{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648183"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:51:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:51:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.13,0.13,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78517"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26895"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78517"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe popliteal fossa is a diamond-shaped space located at the back of the knee joint. It is an important anatomical region containing several neurovascular structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles forms part of the border of the popliteal fossa?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adductor longus","Gracilis","Rectus femoris","Sartorius","Semimembranosus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esemimembranosus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle forms the superomedial border of the popliteal fossa. The other borders are formed by the biceps femoris (superolateral), the medial and lateral heads of the gastrocnemius (inferomedial and inferolateral), and the plantaris muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGracilis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the medial thigh and does not contribute to the popliteal fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectus femoris\u003C/strong\u003E - This is part of the quadriceps group and is located anteriorly, not contributing to the popliteal fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESartorius\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle runs along the anterior thigh and does not form part of the popliteal fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is located in the medial thigh and does not contribute to the popliteal fossa\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The popliteal fossa is a diamond-shaped space located at the back of the knee joint.","The borders of the popliteal fossa are formed by specific muscles and tendons.","The semimembranosus muscle forms the superomedial border of the popliteal fossa."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T08:58:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T08:58:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78517"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attribut